      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "PIV velocity field comparison at 2500 RPM, 5 LPM",
      "description": "Computational velocity magnitudes compared against particle image velocimetry measurements in the pump volute. Mean absolute error 4.2% across 1800 measurement points. Turbulence model (SST k-omega) captures recirculation zones within 6% of experimental values. Aleatory variability in flow conditions is discussed qualitatively in the validation report; pump inlet turbulence intensity varied ±0.8% across repeated PIV runs, and this scatter is noted in the narrative but no formal UQ artifact has been linked to characterize this source of aleatory uncertainty.",
      "hasUncertaintyQuantification": "https://uofa.net/morrison/uq/uq-01-velocity-field-epistemic"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/vr-02-pressure-rise",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Pump pressure rise validation across 5 operating points",
      "description": "Predicted head-flow curve compared against bench-top hydraulic measurements at five flow-speed combinations (3–7 LPM, 2000–3500 RPM). Normalized RMS error is 3.8%. Experimental repeatability was assessed across three pump specimens; specimen-to-specimen variability was 2.1% and is acknowledged in the validation narrative as a source of aleatory uncertainty inherent to manufacturing tolerances. No formal UQ node is linked for this result; the uncertainty discussion remains in prose form only.",
      "hasUncertaintyQuantification": "https://uofa.net/morrison/uq/uq-02-pressure-rise-combined"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/vr-03-hemolysis-index",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Relative hemolysis index prediction vs. in-vitro measurement",
      "description": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) compared against in-vitro blood damage measurements using bovine blood at 37°C. Computed RH values for worst-case operating point: 0.81 (predicted) vs. 0.85 ± 0.09 (measured, n=6). The ±0.09 experimental scatter reflects biological variability in red blood cell fragility across blood lots, which constitutes a significant aleatory uncertainty source. This variability is discussed in the discussion section of the validation report and acknowledged as irreducible. The result meets the RH < 1 acceptance criterion. No hasUncertaintyQuantification link is provided for this validation result; the aleatory component associated with inter-lot biological variability is therefore uncharacterized in the structured evidence record."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/vr-04-wall-shear-stress",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Wall shear stress distribution comparison at blade leading edge",
      "description": "Computed wall shear stress contours at the impeller blade leading edge compared against micro-PIV near-wall measurements. Peak shear stress predicted within 8% of measured values. Mesh sensitivity analysis confirms discretization error contribution below 3%. Aleatory uncertainty from day-to-day variation in experimental flow conditions is bounded by repeated measurements and formally characterized in the linked UQ node.",
      "hasUncertaintyQuantification": "https://uofa.net/morrison/uq/uq-04-wss-aleatory-bound"
    }
